WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.680
JJ, definitely one of my programming heroes. There's many things that are incredible about JJ,

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:11.840
but the thing that I find most incredible is his willingness to move from an area where he is like

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:19.040
an expert and knows it down pat to a new area where he knows nothing. And that I think is just

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:24.240
like an incredible...like that's sort of incredibly brave and an incredible tool to be able to say

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:30.400
like, I'm a master. I've mastered this and now I'm going to go over here and become a novice again.

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:36.560
But I just have a huge amount of admire. I've become a big fanboy of the DuckDB creators

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:41.200
like Mark and Hannes. I know Rachel mentioned that they had their Data Science Hangout on Thursday

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:50.480
with Hannes. In addition to being just super nice people, occasionally a bit sarcastic and

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:57.040
with very dry humor. They're really great people and really collaborative. And I've just been

00:00:57.040 --> 00:01:04.000
impressed with their willingness to take on any problem and say, oh, we're unfazed by

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.400
we're going to make DuckDB work on this problem. We're going to make DuckDB do this or do that.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:13.919
And so I think what they've been able to accomplish with a small team, kind of run

00:01:13.919 --> 00:01:19.199
circles around many startups that have a hundred engineers and just goes to show that it isn't

00:01:19.199 --> 00:01:24.080
about the number of developers working on a project. That small teams of people who are

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:30.639
really, really focused and motivated can really accomplish great things.

